Hola, Welcome to my second ever journal for Hackclub, but first ever submitted. In this journal, I will be going over the entire period it took me
to create the phone stand, which I started on July 12, 2026, to today, July 17, 2026.

July 12, 2026, Day 1 (Beginning)
_________________________________________________________________________________________
I started this project on the day illustrated above with a simple brainstorming at 2:04 PM EST, or 14:04. Upon my last hackclub experience, 
which I unfortunately did not meet the deadline for, I had a good idea about what I was doing to complete a project. Additionally, due to 
the time I used scouring the hackclub site a day earlier, (while I was away from my workstation), I had envisioned what I wanted to do already, which
made the planning stage much easier (This is illustrated in my first and second recordings in the video links, titled the beginning in the Video 
Links tab). As I was still in the midst of another project, which I hadn't given up on yet (nor have I to this day), I stopped after this point and
went back to work on my clock project after gaining new skills in onshape, as demonstrated by the few certificates I earned in the onshape learning
center.

July 13, 2026, Day 2
_________________________________________________________________________________________
I resumed my work on this project, which I had now deemed to be a phone stand, at 9:51 PM EST (just assume my region to be EST for all following time 
iterations), starting a project for it on CAD after a long, 2 hour and 22 minute session of frustratedly working on the clock (previous project) on
onshape. With the impending due date, and a want to do something productive (much of the time working on the clock amounted to little due to 
inexperience), I started modeling the sketch I brainstormed, seen by my 24 minute session distinguishable with the name El Principio. After the time I
spent trying to fix the same problems over and over again, it felt nice to be able to do some concrete work. After this point, I stopped in good spirits,
to continue on the next day.

July 14, 2026, Day 3
_________________________________________________________________________________________
On this day, I worked for about 3 hours and 13 minutes on the project, as shown by the videos La Construccion (2h 56 min) and Divots (15 min). In the
first of which, started at 2:43 PM, I spent a lot of time designing the main body of the phone case and it's functions. I did get caught up in this a
while, stuck on how I was going to make my ideas a reality, but I ended up figuring it out. For example, I had made the decision to make the bottom halves
of the clamps spin up rather than having the threaded rods spin upwards, as I thought that individuals are more likely to have space available under their
desk to contain the rods rather than above, as it poses a hazard and is quite an annoyance. Moreover, I was also seeing difficulties in making the puzzle
connection that I wanted in the base clamp to extend the range of the phone stand track, but after some google searches (which to foreshadow, happens 
frequently in the timelapses due to the fact that I don't know what I am doing) I was able to get it working using surfaces (drawings extruded (one of or 
the only way to make one)). During the end of La Construccion period, I had started work on the pivot point which allowed the contraption to move in
a circle.

Starting back up at 9:13, I had worked to finish the Pivot Point, as I called it then (Base Pivot now), adding details with many extrusions and the help
of the pattern feature. After I had made one divot using the revolve feature (which took me a minute to understand, as much did), I was able to use the
circular pattern feature to make 72 of them. I had decided 72 instead of something like 36 or something like that for two reasons, empty space and
pivotability. After making the 36, it didn't feel like enough, with 10 degrees of motion as the standard movement (though the user can move between the
divots at their leisure), so I doubled it to make it 5 degrees, suiting my preferences much better. After I finished these designs, I went to bed earlier
than usual, as I had to work the next day.

